ort or resistance lvls. this is just not true. a lot of lvls we need only to have a pic of characteristic. when the positioning shifts to long to short skew or vice versa territory, you can expect different spot/vol correlation, hedging flows etc. different sentiment\nthe interesting part is when those lvls are \"guarded\" like it was on monday (03 feb) that i wrote in the weekly post, and made me long that downstick and there we go, market rallied\nas said, when you buy an option, you buy vol. you bet on or against the IV on it. what is vol? the SD of the long returns. what does it mean? how much SD is expected for the price action. as I showed in the post about vol, this assumption is based on gaussian distribution, or normal distribution (same concept). it is symmetrical, every sigma values have a probability values.\nwe can take the IV of a contract, multiply it by 1/sqrt(252) and so it reveals us the 1 sigma range that the market bets on for that contract alone.\nthe common practice is to take the ATM IV on lets say weekly expo. some use the ruole of 16, bcs sqrt(252) is close to 16... \"good enough\" my calculation is a bit more complex, but the idea is to take the ranges that the market bets on\nimplied vol is the bet on volatility. Buffett said: price is what you pay, value is what you get. same with vol: IV is the price, RV is the value\n*\njust to make it clear for everyone. When I\u0027m talking about risk, i talk about this: Lets say the both of these start and end points are the same starting and ending values . So you can go from A to B with lower risk, lower SD, and higher risk higher SD. this is why idon\u0027t take longer term position. \nhedging is a continuous process to stay as delta-neutral as possible, dynamic hedging is not a binary “start–reverse” process. Also MMs can use options, correlated instruments to hedge gamma risk.\nadn don\u0027t forget that they hedge a complex portfolio. so aggregate gamma is smoother than what one sees in a single-option model\nalso MMs avoid executing one large, end-of-day reversal. instead of this, they unwind their hedges gradually during the session so they prevent a sudden spike in trading volume, bcs the unwinding process is spread over time\ndelta is overrated and misunderstood between retails and some services\nwhenever you long an option, you long the gamma (long \u003d positive short \u003d negative)\nMM takes the opposite of the trade.  so he will be short gamma.\nnow imagine that you long an 50 delta call, with a gamma of lets say 2 MM will have  -50 delta call with gamma of -2 he has -50 delta, so he buys 50 shres of stock (1 delta assets, as we call them, futures, stocks.. but not true for VIX futs!!!) \nNow if spot moves up by 1 pt, you add the gamma to the delta like: (-50) + (-2) \u003d -52 so the MM became shorter delta, he has to buy 2 more shares of stocks so he buys into the direction. \nif the spot moves down, you simply extract the gamma values from the delta: (-50) - (-2) \u003d -50 +2 \u003d -48 so now, MM only need to have 48 shares of stock, so he will sell 2 shares.  So again, he is hedging into the price direction.\n"},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"i.2","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0,"ln_c2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0}},"i_pid":null,"eo_mb":0.0,"i_ht":98.35188976377952,"eo_rtdf":{"rdf_ft":0},"eo_ml":0.0,"eo_mr":0.0,"eo_ad":null,"i_cid":"s-blob-v1-IMAGE-CP46VqFXnGk","i_cont":0.0,"eo_mt":0.0,"eo_type":0,"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"","lc_ct":0,"lc_sci":"","lc_srk":""},"i_wth":401.6588188976378,"eo_at":null,"i_iwc":{"iwc_w":false},"eo_hb":false,"eo_rtd":"","i_crop":{"crop_oxr":-0.0,"crop_oyr":-0.0,"crop_rot":0.0,"crop_hr":1.0,"crop_wr":1.0},"i_iw":false,"i_rot":0.0,"i_clst":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[]}},"i_bri":0.0,"i_msct":0,"i_src":null,"i_opa":1.0}}},{"ty":"te","id":"i.2","spi":6398},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":4218,"ei":4218,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":false,"