y:\nif vol goes up, he must ask more for the contract, \nif vol goes down, he is fine with lower price, bcs his risk is lower bcs the probability of you winning the bet changing\nbut we don\u0027t know what the future volatility will be tomorrow, or into friday... we have stochvol models to assume... but at the end of the day what we get is a tons of bet on the future volatility for the next day, for the day after, for 5 days later etc. this is called IMPLED VOLATILIY\nso if you buy a 6050 5DTE call, you have the strike, the time to expo, spot and risk-free-rate... these four parameters are well defined.\nthe 5th input of the option pricing model is volatility itself, and MMs can play with that now listen very carefully, and i hope you have read my post about betting: if we assume that the market is efficient, we say that plp there have all the necessary infos (insiders included) to estimate the future value of a stock right. so if more and more plp start to bet on this 6050 SPX by friday, the demand of that call contract will elevate.\nwhat does it mean? this means that plp see high probability that the bet will be a winner.\nwhat does it mean for the market maker? it means that he has a significant risk exposure by selling that contract,\nso what will he do? pricing it higher. \nhow? through the volatility input. so the implied vol (IV) of that contract will elevate or in other words: the vol risk premium of that contract will go up, bcs in order to get to 6050 by friday, you need a market with higher weekly vol bcs don\u0027t forget that vol is the SD of logreturns‼️ And by this the premium naturally will elevate on that contract \nthe opposite happens, if we still assume efficient market, and the plp don\u0027t like this bet, and don\u0027t want to bet on 6050 by friday. in this case plp won\u0027t buy that contract, and so the demand for that contract will decrease relative to the supply, so market makers will lower the vol risk premium on it. \nhow? again, changing the vol input but this is not an out-of-nowhere process, and THIS IS KEY! Listen it all depends on WHAT IS THE PREMIUM THAT THE BUYERS ARE WILLING TO PAY FOR THAT BET like in an auction and this will determine the premium, and so the size of the vol risk premium by changing the IV input so this is all reflexive. \ndo you get it? very reflexive. this is why we say, buying/selling vol. \nwhen we say \"long vol\", it means long an option. why? bcs you long the IV on that contract. you bet on that IV to realize and when we say \"short vol\" it is the opposite: selling an option, bcs you bet against that IV/premium also this can be called as \"vega\" in MM terms/floor jargon bcs vega is the function of that IV input\nand how market makers hedge vega? well... through other options. bcs only options have vega exposure but vega\u0027s influence is longer-term. it has no effect in the short-term. forget that no intraday vega effect...\n"},{"ty":"ae","et":"list","id":"kix.list.3","epm":{"le_nb":{"nl_4":{"b_gf":"%4","b_ts":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_sc":false,"ts_it_i":true,"ts_fgc2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0},"ts_st_i":true,"ts_bgc2":{"hclr_color":null,"clr_type":0},"ts_fs_i":true,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_bgc2_i":true,"ts_it":false,"ts_va":"nor","ts_bd_i":true,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Courier New","ts_st":false,"ts_bd":false,"ts_fgc2_i":true,"ts_sc_i":true,"ts_tw":400},"b_ifl":162.0,"b_gs":"o","b_a":0,"b_sn":1,"b_gt":9,"b_il":180.0},"nl_3":{"b_gf":"%3","b_ts":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_sc":false,"ts_it_i":true,"ts_fgc2":{"hclr_color":"#000000","clr_type":0},"ts_st_i":true,"ts_bgc2":{"hclr_color":null,"clr_type":0},"ts_fs_i":true,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_bgc2_i":true,"ts_it":false,"ts_va":"nor","ts_bd_i":true,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Noto Sans Symbols","ts_st":false,"ts_bd":false,"ts_fgc2_i":true,"ts_sc_i":true,"ts_tw":400},"b_ifl":126.0,"b_gs":"●","b_a":0,"b_sn":1,"b_gt":9,"b_il":144.0},"nl_2":{"b_gf":"%2","b_ts":{"ts_un":false,"ts